{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487029","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487029"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:54:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:54:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"236"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"236","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/236"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.07,0.09,0.53,0.24]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"236"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111995"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"236","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/236"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"236"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94059"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"377"},{"type":"tags","id":"414"},{"type":"tags","id":"1196"},{"type":"tags","id":"2044"},{"type":"tags","id":"8066"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"},{"type":"tags","id":"8149"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"934"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4178"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13583"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14372"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111995","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111995"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 63-year-old woman presents to her General Practitioner with a unifocal 2.5 cm suspicious lesion in the upper outer quadrant of her right breast found on screening mammography. A core needle biopsy shows an invasive breast carcinoma, classified grade 3, oestrogen and progesterone-positive, HER2 receptor-negative.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe undergoes wide local excision of the breast and sentinel lymph node biopsy which shows complete resection of the tumour with clear surgical margins and metastatic disease in three sentinel nodes. An axillary lymph node dissection is performed in which three additional positive lymph nodes are identified.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following treatment recommendations is most appropriate?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Letrozole","Completion mastectomy","Radiotherapy and trastuzumab","Chemotherapy, radiotherapy plus letrozole","Radiotherapy and letrozole"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDue to the size of the tumour being small (\u0026lt;3cm), a wide local excision was the appropriate degree of surgical resection. The breast margins are clear, so a \u003Cstrong\u003Ecompletion mastectomy\u003C/strong\u003E is not necessary. The sentinel LN biopsy showed three positive nodes, explaining why an axillary lymph node dissection was done. Where breast-conserving surgery (wide local excision) is chosen, \u003Cstrong\u003Eradiotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E is almost always indicated afterwards.\u00a0Multi-agent \u003Cstrong\u003Echemotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E reduces the risk of recurrence and death for women with node positive breast cancer (up to the age of 70), hence this should be included in her management recommendations. The current evidence suggests several months of combination chemotherapy is recommended and is more effective than single agent chemotherapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAromatase inhibitors such as \u003Cstrong\u003Eletrozole\u003C/strong\u003E are a hormonal option for ER-positive tumours in post-menopausal women. Tamoxifen can be used, but carries the increased risk of endometrial cancer, stroke and DVT, and is less efficacious than aromatase inhibitors in post-menopausal women.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrastuzumab\u003C/strong\u003E is used in HER2 positive breast cancer, which is not the case here.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Treatment of breast cancer is tailored to the individual and their specific tumours and pathological findings","Higher grade cancers and those involving the lymph nodes will require chemotherapy unless other contraindications/patient factors"],"references":["Mayer EL, Burstein HJ. Postmenopausal breast cancer: a best endocrine strategy? Lancet. 2015;386(10001):1317-1319. Available at:\u00a0https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(15)61206-5/fulltext.","Heilat G, Brennan M, French J. Update on the management of early-stage breast cancer. Aust J Gen Pract. 2019;48:604-8. Available at:\u00a0https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2019/september/management-of-early-stage-breast-cancer.","Clinical practice guidelines for the management of early breast cancer: second edition.\u00a0In: National Breast Cancer Centre [online]. 2001. Available at: https://www.canceraustralia.gov.au/sites/default/files/publications/cpg-clinical-practice-guidelines-management-early-breast-cancer_504af03111a52.pdf."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94059"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"236"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94059","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94059"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-23T09:49:07+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-23T09:49:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"236"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111995"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updat